data.name: textBoxConfigurationPath.ToolTip
data.value: The configuration path is the path where TEAM stores, and interfaces with, its configuration files. If this directory does not exist it will be created with default files (assuming sufficient priviliges to do so are in place at OS level).

data.name: textBoxStagingAreaPrefix.ToolTip
data.value:
The convention that identifies / classifies Data Objects as Standing, or Landing, area objects. This is used in colour coding and understanding of the direction of processing.
The Staging Area is typically used to (often temporarily) store data in the data platform, before it is processed further.
This label is used in conjunction with the prefix/suffix setting. If the prefix is used, the label will be used to identify the object based on the start of the non-qualified name.
E.g. stg.STG_EXAMPLE or simply STG_EXAMPLE will be evaluated as 'Staging' if the prefix is selected.

data.name: textBoxPSAPrefix.ToolTip
data.value:
The convention that identifies / classifies Data Objects as Persistent Staging Area objects. This is used in colour coding and understanding of the direction of processing.
The Persistent Staging Area is the memory of the data platform, storing all transactions that pass through the system to faciliate refactoring of other layers and areas.
This label is used in conjunction with the prefix/suffix setting. If the prefix is used, the label will be used to identify the object based on the start of the non-qualified name.
E.g. dbo.PSA_EXAMPLE or simply PSA_EXAMPLE will be evaluated as 'Persistent Staging' if the prefix is selected.

data.name: grpTableName.ToolTip
data.value:
The prefix/suffix setting refers to the way Data Objects are evaluated for their type or classification.
This setting directs where the evaluation is done, at the start of the name or at the back. Evaluation is done against non-qualified Data Object names, meaning the schema is removed from the evaluation.

data.name: groupBox1.ToolTip
data.value:
The key location prefix/suffix setting refers to the way the keys are expected for Data Objects.
During metadata validation and activation, the TEAM application needs to understand how (business) keys are defined, so that the right metadata can be combined. For this, keys need to be identified and this setting directs how this identification works. It is combined with the key label as set in the 'Data Warehouse generic' tab page.

data.name: groupBox8.ToolTip
data.value:
This is a special setting for the Persistent Staging Area only, to determine the natural key. Either an index can be used to understand the natural key, or a primary key.
The idea is that the key (plus an effective date/time stamp) will show the TEAM application what the natural key is, but for this it needs to know which convention is used.

data.name: textBoxSourceRowId.ToolTip
data.value:
The Row Id (aka Source Row Id) is meant to be used as sequential number used within batch processing.
With the Row Id, every individual row can be identified in order of processing by a given batch process.

data.name: textBoxEventDateTime.ToolTip
data.value:
The Event Date/Time attribute is meant to capture the moment of change for the record in/by the originating system.
While the LDTS is the moment the change was received by the Data Platform, the Event Date/Time is the moment the change was triggered or committed in the source system.

data.name: textBoxDWHKeyIdentifier.ToolTip
data.value:
This label captures the naming convention for the Data Platform / Data Warehouse key.
In most scenarios, supplementary Data Warehouse keys are necessary to track changes over time and/or otherwise uniquely identify data in the data solution.
TEAM will use this convention to evaluate (calculations of) business keys during the activation routines.

data.name: textBoxSatelliteAlternativeLDTSAttribute.ToolTip
data.value:
In some scenarios, it may be required to provide an name of the load date/time stamp (LDTS) for a Context ('Satellite') type Data Object.
For example, in some Data Objects 'load date' may be used as attribute name for the LDTS - whereas for a Context type object this could be called 'effective date'.
In most use-cases, the same attribute is used in all Data Objects. But this option is provided just in case.

data.name: textBoxHubAlternativeLDTSAttribute.ToolTip
data.value:
In some scenarios, it may be required to provide an name of the load date/time stamp (LDTS) for a Core Business Concept (CBC) type Data Object.
For example, in some Data Objects 'effective date' may be used as attribute name for the LDTS whereas for a CBC this is called 'first seen date'.
In most use-cases, the same attribute is used in all Data Objects. But this option is provided just in case.

data.name: textBoxAlternativeRecordSource.ToolTip
data.value:
In some scenarios, it may be required to provide an alternative record source field or identifier.
For example, if string values (full names) are used in the Staging Layer but identifiers are used upstream.
In most use-cases, the same record source is used everywhere but this option is provided just in case.

data.name: textBoxRecordSource.ToolTip
data.value:
This label captures the attribute name of the Record Source / name.
This is a pointer that can also be set in the data logistics control framework (e.g. DIRECT) but if used as independent attribute the name can be provided here.

data.name: textBoxLDST.ToolTip
data.value:
This label captures the attribute name that represents the Load Date/Time Stamp (LDTS).
The LDTS captured the moment the data environment receives data, ideally as early as possible in the solution.

data.name: textBoxHubTablePrefix.ToolTip
data.value:
This label will be used to evaluate the type of Data Object, and by extent, the data loading (or interpretation) vector.
This particular label will be used to identify a Core Business Concept object based on the non-qualified name (excluding schema).
For instance, HUB_CUSTOMER will be evaluated as Core Business Concept for the label 'HUB' and prefix/suffix setting as per the Prefixes and Suffixes tab.

data.name: textBoxSatPrefix.ToolTip
data.value:
This label will be used to evaluate the type of Data Object, and by extent, the data loading (or interpretation) vector.
This particular label will be used to identify a Context object based on the non-qualified name (excluding schema).
For instance, SAT_CUSTOMER will be evaluated as Concept entity for the label 'SAT' and prefix/suffix setting as per the Prefixes and Suffixes tab.

data.name: textBoxLinkTablePrefix.ToolTip
data.value:
This label will be used to evaluate the type of Data Object, and by extent, the data loading (or interpretation) vector.
This particular label will be used to identify a Natural Business Relationship object based on the non-qualified name (excluding schema).
For instance, LNK_RENEWAL will be evaluated as Natural Business Relationship for the label 'LINK' and prefix/suffix setting as per the Prefixes and Suffixes tab.

data.name: textBoxLinkSatPrefix.ToolTip
data.value:
This label will be used to evaluate the type of Data Object, and by extent, the data loading (or interpretation) vector.
This particular label will be used to identify a Natural Business Object Context object based on the non-qualified name (excluding schema).
For instance, LSAT_RENEWAL_DETAIL will be evaluated as a relationship Context entity for the label 'LSAT' and prefix/suffix setting as per the Prefixes and Suffixes tab.

data.name: tabPageConnectionMain.ToolTip
data.value:
Connections are set per environment, so the connections as configured for the active environment are displayed here in tab pages.
Each connection can be linked to a Data Object Mapping, one for the source- and one for the target Data Object. The schema name that is set in the connection will be used to evaluate the fully qualified name (schema + table name) across TEAM.
New connections can be created by clicking on the empty tab.

data.name: richTextBoxConnectionMain.Text
data.value:
Create new data connections so these can be assigned to metadata.
A unique connection for the metadata repository needs to be assigned from the available connections. All connections can be assigned to metadata mappings.

data.name: tabPageEnvironmentMain.ToolTip
data.value:
The 'environments' acts as logical separations of work in TEAM. They are akin to tenants where you can setup different environments each with their own connections and content.
An environment is the top-level separation in TEAM, and is used to define either a project or layer depending on preferences.
Internally, an environment is identified with an environment key. At any time an environment is active, and the current one can be viewed or changed / selected here.

data.name: groupBoxEnvironmentBehaviour.ToolTip
data.value:
This radio button direct how technical metadata is collected when processing the mappings in TEAM.
Virtual Mode will not make any database calls (e.g. to the catalog, data dictionary) and use the physical model information that is available in the Data Grids in TEAM.
Physical Mode on the other hand will not use any stored information in the Data Grid (Physical Model tab) on the Manage Metadata screen and directly query the database using the defined connections to fetch physical model details.
Examples are ordinal positions, data types etc.

data.name: richTextBoxEnvironmentsInformation.Text
data.value:
The overview and management of working environments.
Environments are the main tenant in TEAM and capture all further configuration settings. All subsequent tabs are applicable for the selected working environment.
